review_blob: Clear golden, white long lasting head. Aroma is faint hops and somewhat buttery/butterscotch aroma, a little off. Flavor is nice bitterness, followed by a bit too much alcohol, ends with a little alcohol warmth. Maybe a bit too sweet too be palatable.
beer_name: Borg lfur lfur Double IPA Nr. 17

review_blob:
Pours deep amber with a one finger head. Head dissapated quickly. Deep amber color, beautiful in the glass.

Aroma is dark fruits, malt, and a lot of sweetness.

Taste is sweet, mainly malty and a bit sweet, with enough bitterness to gently balance it. More dark fruits, a little burnt caramel and some spicyness, that i reckon is from the hops not the yeast. A little warming alcohol in the finish like you would expect in a beer of this type.

Overall a solid doppelbock. Should be noted that this bottle is about a year old and has had some time to mellow out.

Havent rated for a while now, but i have to now. Just bought a pricey Delirium Red at ATVR, licquer store in Iceland. About 4.5$ for a 0.33 ceramic bottle of this.

Pours nicely, looks beautifly red in the glass, small white to pink fast dissapating head. Then it starts.

The aroma of this is horribly artificial. Its loke from a pack of cheap bubblegum, overly sweet and one dimentional.

Taste is just like the aroma, cloying, way too sweet and artificial.

How i wish i could just get my money back, poured most off it down the drain. Will definetly not buy again.

Pours golden and a bit hazy with a one finger head. Lively carbonation visible in the glass.

Aroma is really spicey with a mild barnyard note, hay. 

Taste is unlike any other blond ive had. Mouthfeel comes of kind of light and thin, folloved by nice spicey bitterness. Then there are really earthy notes in it. The beer is carbonated and not at all refreshing as a blond often is.

Overall a different type of beer from what i would have guessed it to be.

Pours a light straw color with a nice white quick falling head.

Aroma is traditional wheat, with citrus, spices (mostly coriander).

The beer is lively on the palate, a bit thin and watery. Finishes off with some spices and then some low bitterness.

An ok, beer, but my least favorite of the LaTrappe beers.

Pours a deep golden colour whit two finger white head. Quicly dissolves.

Aroma is banana with faint hinst of bubblegum.

Mouthfeel is medium with light carbonation.

Taste is spicy, nicely sweet balancing off with faint hop bitterness towards the end. Very well balanced off even though it may seem to sweet for some. A nice refreshing summer beer. Every sip demands another.

A nice refreshing, spicy belgian beer. Very "belgian",

Pours opaque with yeast floating around in it. Massive beige head that quickly falls.

Aroma is malts, and bitter chockolate.

Mouthfeel is medium low to low with medium high carbonation. Taste is roasted malts up front that turn into a nice bitterness, finishing off in licqurish and some bitter chokolate.

Overall a really nice stout.

Pours almost opaque (hints of copper color when held to light) with a nice 2 finger head that dissolves quickly lacing the glass nicely. Looks really good.

Aroma is heavy toffee, burnt coffee beans followed by an almost milk chockolate like aroma.

Moutfeel is thick, rich and creamy. Malt bitterness up front turning into nice rich chockolate flavor at the end of the sip, followed by a lingering hop balance. Once sip screams for another. Carbonation is medium to low suiting the style perfectly.

Overall a superb porter.

Pours a dark cherry colour with brown to pink-ish small head.

Aroma is sweet and mostly cherries.

Mouthfeel is light to medium with nice high carbonation.
Taste is heavy cherry up front which then turns into a green apple sour/tart flavor that dries up. Ends really dry.

Overall a nice beer, but i dislike the really sour dry taste it leaves in the mouth.

Pours a cloudy yellowish, golden colour with frothy head that fell quickly.

Aroma is banana, cloves and yeast/bread.

The beer is very lively on the tounge, well carbonated and you can feel the alcohol a tad.
Still a very refreshing beer, very spicy and very refreshing. Could sneak up on you at 7.7%. Beautifly balanced

Pours deep brown with an off tan two finger head. Head lasts for a while.
Little too no lacing, deep amber hue.

Aroma is sweet with mainly malt, caramel, and some sour tang.
Caramel malt and dark fruits.

Medium body, nice mouthfeel, beer is very lively with high carbonation.
Roasted malt bitterness, really spicy, and very well balanced. LaTrappe yeast signature flavor.

A nice bockbier and another great latrappe bier.

Pours black with red hue. Small tan head that fell quickly.

Aroma is heavy on the malt side. No hops noticable. Maybe some dark chocolate and some hint of roastiness.

Medium full body with light carbonation. Roasted malt bitterness shines through. No alcohol warmth at all, very well balanced. Some caramel/toffee noticable in aftertaste.

A nice warmer on a cold dark evening.

Pours a golden colour, nice 3 finger frothy white quickly falling head.
Flakes og yeast floating around in the beer.

Aroma is yeast, spice and banana.

Medium to low mouthfeel, high carboation.
Some alcohol in aftertaste, very mellow for a strong golden. Spices, and subtle spicyness. Balanced and nice to drink.

2010 Version from TVR in Iceland. (Sktuvogur)

Pours black, with reddish hue when held up to light. One finger tan head.

Aroma is heavy malt, and some fruit. Plums and raisins. Anchor beers have a house flavor/aroma very well noticable in this brew.

The mouthfeel is really thin.  Carbonation is really suitable. The beer is a bit sour up front and finishes really dry with massive coffee and chockolate in the aftertaste. The roasted malt bitterness is well noticed.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2005 and later)

review_blob:
Pours a cherry red colour with pink head.

Aroma is very sweet with cherries dominant.

Very light mouthfeel and medium carbonation with sour taste up front, finishes somewhat sweet and some sour tartness.

Nice Kriek, bit pricey in Iceland though.

Pours an amber color with reddish hue. No head.

Aroma is quite hoppy, with caramel and dark fruits in tha background.

Medium moutfeel, beer is rather sweet with some alcohol warmth  and the signature bitterness/flavor from Anchor brewing co.

Drank with some blue cheese and primadonna on Christmas eve, very nice beer!

Pours dark amber with off tan head, dissapates quickly.

Aroma is of vinegar, some dark fruits like plums or dates.

The beers mouthfeel is very light, low carbonation and low tartness.
Hint of caramel and sour berries.

Pours deep copper with red-ish hue, massive off tan head.

Aroma is yeast, hints of banana.

Medium moutfeel, alcohol warmth, taste of candy sugar.

Pours black with red-ish hue. Nice two finger tan head. 

Aroma is of vanilla, and well, chockolate. Not the dark chocolate, but more milk chockolate.

Light to medium light body, low carbonation and heavy cocoa and chockolate flavor.

Interesting to taste, but would not buy again.

Pours deep brown, with some ruby red notes. Massive tan head.

Nice malt in the nose, some toastiness, faint coffee aroma.

The beer has a light to medium mouthfeel. Ends really roasted.
Some liqurish noticable in taste.

A bit too dry for me.

Pours a dark colour with reddish hue. Little to no head.

Malty aroma with some sour elements.

Thin bodied with low carbonation.

Taste is malty with intense bitterness in the finish. 

Thin bodied but an ok ESB. Would prefer Fullers ESB before this.

Pours a deep golden color with a huge froathy white head. Almost creamlike head.

Aroma is piney, grapefruity. Mostly piney.

Medium mouthfeel and low carbonation with huge biterness in the aftertaste. Even though the beer is somewhat sweet, it is still very balanced.

Overall an enjoyable beer.

Pours a golden colour wiht a creamy, long lasting white head. Moderate lacing in the glass.

Aroma is earthy somewhat spicy and dry.

The beer has a nice mouthfeel, light to none carbonation. But saaz spicy hops are dominant.  Nothing close to the average belgian blond.

The beer is quite heavy, much more ale like than belgian blond ales.

Overall a nice beer, but not as refreshing as one would like a blond ale to be.

Pours a copper colour, with off tan to beige long lasting head. Very clear.
Nice lacing in the glass.

Aroma is bready with some nice heavy citrusy hops.

Mothfeel is very light, moderate to light carbonation and finishes of rather bitter. Hoppy yet very drinkable and as refreshing as this high IBU beer gets. Hops have dominant citrus and also some noticable peppers.
Malt in the aftertaste.

Pours a thick tan head, fell quickly. Beer itself is opaque.

Aroma is heavy malt, smoked ham, bacon.

Medium full to full body, creamy. Chockolate, coffee and some smoke. Warm alcohol, maybe a bit too warm. Aftertaste is dark chockolate. Light, balanced carbonation.

Overall a well crafted beer, dont hesitate to try it if you get the chance.

Skl, (cheers).

Pours a beautiful copper colour with a moderate beige head and nice lacing.

Aroma of caramel malts, no noticable hop aroma.

Thick and mouthfilling, low carbonation and taste of burnt caramel, roasted malts and ends in a beautiful bitterness.

One of my all time favorite beers.

Pours a deep golden to coppery colour. 2 finger short lasting head.
Aroma is lightly hoppy, nothing intense, and some dark caramel malts in the nose.

Full rich mouthfeel with light carbonation. Hop bitterness is is dominant. Piney bitterness.

Overall a well crafted drinkable pale ale.

Pours a dark golden colour. Little to no head.
Aroma is not so hoppy, and a little malt is noticable.
Thin watery mouthfeel, high carbonation and a nice hop bitterness towards the end. Long lasting flavor, and a nice drinkable beer.

Aroma similar to the aroma in a sheep farm (where they keep the sheep).
Smokey, heavy.

Appearance is dark, but still you can note some deep copper colour when held up to light. Heavy, thick, three finger foam. Heavy lacing in the glass.

First impression of taste is, smoked meat. Like smoked lamb. Heavy smoke, and malt. Finishes dry on the tongue.

Palate is full, but finishes a bit dry like mentioned earlier.

Overall: A heavy beer probably best suited with a heavy meal.
Nothing special going on here. Drinkable but not a go to beer. Thin and watery.

Pours a ruby red/copper-ish color. Light beige head falls quickly.

A bottle from TVR bought 10. of August 2010. Many bottles still on shelf there, will buy another one and age it.

Malty caramel aroma, hops not noticable in the nose.

Full rich body, medium carbonation. Malty, roasty, hint of burnt caramel, oranges and a hint of spice. Alcohol in aftertaste, but not out of balance, finishes sweet.

Will probably benefit from aging.

Bottle from Barleywine.dk @ 16.9.2010.
Pours golden to light copper. Massive long lasting head.
Yeast aroma dominant. Maybe a hint of banana.
Medium body, high carbonation. Lightly warming with hints of pepper.

Overall a nice beer, even if i like the Chimay Red better.

Bottled from Barleywine.dk in Denmark.

Pours dark ruby red/brown ish. Little brown-ish/beige head, fell quickly. Moderate lacing in the glass.
Roasted sweet aroma. Not much hop aroma, dried fruits.

Light carbonation. Full, creamy texture. Malt, coffee and alcohol warmth. Medium sweetness. A bit too much alcohol in the aftertaste.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine
